\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Quicksort and Tail Bounds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Randomized Quicksort
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Algorithm (num)
* Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, choose a pivot 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 uniformly at random (or with median finding technique from last lecture)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Algorithm (num)
* In linear time, compute 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-}=\{x\in S|x\leq p\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{+}=\{x\in S|x>p\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Algorithm (num)
* Quicksort(
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-},S^{+}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Algorithm (num)
* Return [sorted 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{-}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, sorted 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{+}$
\end_inset

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Randomized Quicksort
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that, up to constant factors, the runtime of Quicksort is equal to
 the number of comparisons made (which is also true for deterministic versions).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 be the random variable representing the number of element pairs compared.
 We also note that when elements 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 are compared, one of them must have been 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so they cannot be compared again.
 Define indicator random variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{ij}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i,j\text{ compared}\\
0 & \text{o.w.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\sum_{i,j}X_{ij}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[T]=\sum_{i.j}\mathbb{E}[X_{ij}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{i,j}\Pr[i,j\text{ compared}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider elements 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 in the final sorted order.
 Without loss of generality, set 
\begin_inset Formula $i<j$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is selected as the pivot before any element between them, then 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{ij}=1$
\end_inset

; otherwise they will be placed in different sets and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now, consider the first time a pivot in 
\begin_inset Formula $\{i,i+1,\dots,j-1,j\}$
\end_inset

 is selected.
 At that point, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr[i\text{ or }j\text{ is pivot}|\text{such a pivot is selected}]=\frac{2}{j+1-i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[T]=\sum_{i,j}\frac{2}{j+1-i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{k=1}^{n-i}\frac{2}{k-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\leq2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\frac{1}{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=2nH(n)\text{ where \ensuremath{H(n)} is the \ensuremath{n^{th}} harmonic number}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\approx2n\log n
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the expected runtime is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta(n\log n)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tail Bounds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Intro to Tail Bounds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Oftentimes, we are interested in high probability guarantees (i.e., that for
 some event 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr[\mathcal{E}]\geq1-p^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 This is especially useful for bounding expectation of maxima and minima
 (something pretty useful as a computer scientist).
 
\series bold
Tail bounds
\series default
 are bounds which show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr[X<\alpha]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For our purposes, we want bounds which guarantee that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr[X\text{ is far from }\mathbb{E}[X]]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general approach for tail bounds is to show that each 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq1-m^{-2}$
\end_inset

 or some other probability close to 1, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the number of variables.
 Then, by the union bound:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[\text{one or more }X_{i}>\alpha]\leq\sum_{i}\Pr[X_{i}>\alpha]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{i}\frac{1}{m^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{1}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[\text{all }X_{i}\leq\alpha]\geq1-\frac{1}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Markov's Inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Markov's Inequality: If 
\begin_inset Formula $X\geq0$
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[X\geq\alpha]\leq\frac{\mathbb{E}[X]}{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
This bound is pretty weak, but can be useful.
 For example, say we play a casino game where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is measured in integer dollars and:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[X_{t+1}|X_{t}=x]=0.9x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
How soon, starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 dollars, until we are broke (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}=0$
\end_inset

) with high probability? First, we know that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[X_{t}]=0.9^{t}n
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
We set a convenient value of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to get a nice expectation and plug it in to Markov:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=2\log_{\frac{1}{0.9}}n\implies\mathbb{E}[X_{t}]=\frac{1}{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[X_{t}\neq0]=\Pr[X_{t}\geq1]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\leq\frac{\frac{1}{n}}{1}\text{ by Markov's inequality}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{1}{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Then, we know that at that 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we are broke with high probability:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[X_{t}=0]=1-\frac{1}{n}\text{ when }t=2\log_{\frac{1}{0.9}}n
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
There is an extended version of Markov's Inequality called Chebyshev bounds,
 which give better bounds when we can calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(X)$
\end_inset

, and in particular if 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(X)\text{ is }\mathcal{O}(\mathbb{E}[X])$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chernoff Bounds 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\bar under
independent
\bar default
 indicator random variables, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\sum_{i}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then, Chernoff bounds state:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[X>(1+\delta)\mu]<\frac{\exp(\delta)}{(1+\delta)^{(1+\delta)}}^{\mu}\text{ }\forall\delta\geq\mathbb{E}[X]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[X<(1+\delta)\mu]<\exp(-\frac{1}{2}\mu\delta^{2})\text{ }\forall\delta\leq\mathbb{E}[X]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\dots,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\bar under
independent
\bar default
 indicator random variables such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\in[a_{i},b_{i}]$
\end_inset

 
\bar under
always
\bar default
, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\sum_{i}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\mathbb{E}[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then, Hoeffding bounds state:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[|X-\mu|\geq\Delta]\leq2\exp(\frac{-2\Delta^{2}}{\sum_{i}(b_{i}-a_{i})^{2}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tail Bounds on Balls and Bins
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 balls and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 bins, distribute the balls across the bins to minimize the maximum number
 of balls in any bin.
 This is a trivial problem if we just evenly distribute the balls, but we
 are interested in the randomized approach as a simple example for usage
 of Chernoff bounds.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the random variable representing the number of balls in bin 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Define indicator random variables:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{ij}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if ball \ensuremath{j} lands in bin \ensuremath{i}}\\
0 & \text{o.w.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{i}=\sum_{j}B_{ij}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}[N_{i}]=\sum_{j}\mathbb{E}[B_{ij}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{n}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we want an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr[N_{i}>\alpha]<m^{-2}$
\end_inset

, so we can apply the union bound.
 Notice that for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are independent, so we can apply Chernoff bounds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[X>(1+\delta)\frac{n}{m}]<\frac{\exp(\delta)}{(1+\delta)^{(1+\delta)}}^{\frac{n}{m}}\text{ }
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want the right side to be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{-2}$
\end_inset

, so we can reverse engineer the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 for which this works.
 We'll consider two special cases; first, the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\exp(\delta)}{(1+\delta)^{(1+\delta)}}<m^{-2}\iff\delta[(1+\delta)\ln(1+\delta)]>2\ln m
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the solution is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta=\Theta(\frac{\log m}{\log\log m})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=1$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[N_{i}>\Theta(\frac{\log m}{\log\log m})]<m^{-2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And by the union bound, all 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta(\frac{\log m}{\log\log m})$
\end_inset

 with probability greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1-m^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 For the second special case, when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=16m\log m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\exp(\delta)}{(1+\delta)^{(1+\delta)}}^{16\log m}<m^{-2}\implies\delta=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=16\log m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr[N_{i}>16\log m]<m^{-2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And by the union bound, all 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $16\log m$
\end_inset

 with probability greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1-m^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

